# Figure 3.0: High-Throughput Scalable Data Model & SQL Optimization Engine
**Portfolio Module: High-Performance Data Lakehouse Calculations**
**Architecture Archetype: Event-Driven Kappa Stream Architecture**

---

## Section 1: Average Daily Consumption Per Meter
This query calculates the arithmetic mean consumption of electricity grouped by individual smart meter devices to establish core household baselines.

```sql
SELECT 
    meter_id,
    ROUND(AVG(usage_kwh), 4) AS average_daily_consumption_kwh
FROM 
    Readings
GROUP BY 
    meter_id
ORDER BY 
    average_daily_consumption_kwh DESC;
```

---

## Section 2: Standard Deviation of Usage Per Meter
This query measures consumption variance per device, which serves as the underlying statistical calculation used to trigger real-time theft alerts and automated field technician dispatches.

```sql
SELECT 
    meter_id,
    ROUND(STDDEV(usage_kwh), 4) AS consumption_standard_deviation,
    COUNT(reading_id) AS total_readings_evaluated
FROM 
    Readings
GROUP BY 
    meter_id
HAVING 
    COUNT(reading_id) > 1;
```

---

## Section 3: Point-in-Time Temporal Join (Historical Pricing Changes)
This script solves the static tariff trap by completely removing dependencies on any static meter-level tariff foreign keys. Instead, it executes a deterministic dual-range temporal join across the `Meter_Tariff_History` associative table and the `Tariffs` Slowly Changing Dimension (SCD Type 2) windows to pinpoint the exact pricing contract active at the precise millisecond of consumption. It leverages an enterprise high-date fallback ('9999-12-31') to ensure absolute query determinism during financial audits.

```sql
SELECT 
    m.hashed_customer_id,
    r.meter_id,
    r.reading_date,
    r.usage_kwh,
    t.tariff_id,
    t.price_per_kwh,
    ROUND(r.usage_kwh * COALESCE(t.price_per_kwh, 0.0000), 4) AS calculated_daily_cost
FROM 
    Readings r
JOIN 
    Meters m ON r.meter_id = m.meter_id
-- Step 1: Pinpoint the specific contract plan assigned to this meter on the date of consumption
JOIN 
    Meter_Tariff_History mth ON r.meter_id = mth.meter_id 
    AND r.reading_date >= mth.assigned_date 
    AND r.reading_date <= COALESCE(mth.removal_date, CAST('9999-12-31' AS DATE))
-- Step 2: Fetch the exact active rate details for that plan on that same historical date window
JOIN 
    Tariffs t ON mth.tariff_id = t.tariff_id
    AND r.reading_date >= t.effective_start 
    AND r.reading_date <= COALESCE(t.effective_end, CAST('9999-12-31' AS DATE));
```

---

## Section 4: Late-Data Arrival Tracking & Incorrectly Billed Invoices
This advanced analytics query identifies out-of-order telemetry payloads that arrived after invoices were compiled. By evaluating the meter's current plan on the late ingestion date versus its historical plan on the actual consumption date, it calculates pricing deltas. It enforces a strict mathematical audit trail for the Figure 4.0 RECONCILIATION queue by isolating late payloads arriving outside the 24-hour transmission window.

```sql
SELECT 
    r.reading_id,
    r.meter_id,
    r.reading_date,
    r.timestamp_received,
    ROUND(COALESCE(t.price_per_kwh, 0.1500), 4) AS applied_billed_price,
    ROUND(actual_t.price_per_kwh, 4) AS correct_historical_price,
    ROUND(COALESCE(t.price_per_kwh, 0.1500) - actual_t.price_per_kwh, 4) AS pricing_delta_error
FROM 
    Readings r
JOIN 
    Meters m ON r.meter_id = m.meter_id
-- Track down the temporary tariff plan mapped to the meter on the late date the system processed the payload
LEFT JOIN 
    Meter_Tariff_History mth_temp ON r.meter_id = mth_temp.meter_id
    AND CAST(r.timestamp_received AS DATE) >= mth_temp.assigned_date 
    AND CAST(r.timestamp_received AS DATE) <= COALESCE(mth_temp.removal_date, CAST('9999-12-31' AS DATE))
LEFT JOIN 
    Tariffs t ON mth_temp.tariff_id = t.tariff_id
    AND CAST(r.timestamp_received AS DATE) >= t.effective_start 
    AND CAST(r.timestamp_received AS DATE) <= COALESCE(t.effective_end, CAST('9999-12-31' AS DATE))
-- Locate the true, compliant contract rate that legally applied on the actual date of consumption
JOIN 
    Meter_Tariff_History mth_actual ON r.meter_id = mth_actual.meter_id
    AND r.reading_date >= mth_actual.assigned_date 
    AND r.reading_date <= COALESCE(mth_actual.removal_date, CAST('9999-12-31' AS DATE))
JOIN 
    Tariffs actual_t ON mth_actual.tariff_id = actual_t.tariff_id
    AND r.reading_date >= actual_t.effective_start 
    AND r.reading_date <= COALESCE(actual_t.effective_end, CAST('9999-12-31' AS DATE))
WHERE 
    COALESCE(t.price_per_kwh, 0.1500) <> actual_t.price_per_kwh
    AND r.timestamp_received > (r.reading_date + INTERVAL '1 day');
```' DAY);
```
